{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17628122","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17628122"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:54:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:54:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17179"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17179","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17179"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9869"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75866"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9869","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9869"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17179"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61379"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"164"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23134"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23136"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75866","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75866"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of severe, right-sided headaches occurring once or twice daily. Each episode lasts 30-45 minutes and awakens him from sleep. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He works as an accountant and does not smoke. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. During the consultation, he develops severe right-sided periorbital pain associated with right-sided facial flushing and eye watering.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following symptoms is most commonly associated with this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lacrimation","Visual scotoma","Photophobia","Neck stiffness","Nausea"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of a cluster headache, characterised by severe unilateral periorbital pain occurring in clusters over weeks to months. \u003Cstrong\u003ELacrimation\u003C/strong\u003E is one of the most characteristic autonomic features, occurring in over 80% of patients. Other autonomic symptoms include nasal congestion, rhinorrhoea, facial sweating, and ptosis on the affected side.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVisual scotoma\u003C/strong\u003E is more commonly associated with migraine headaches, particularly during the aura phase. Cluster headaches typically do not have associated visual symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhotophobia\u003C/strong\u003E while common in migraine headaches, is not a common feature of cluster headaches. Patients with cluster headaches often remain active during attacks, unlike migraine sufferers who prefer to lie still in a dark room.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeck stiffness\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with meningitis or cervicogenic headaches. While cluster headache patients may experience neck discomfort, it is not a defining feature.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENausea\u003C/strong\u003E is more commonly associated with migraine headaches. Cluster headaches usually do not cause significant gastrointestinal symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECluster headaches are more common in men and typically begin between ages 20-40. The pain is strictly unilateral and typically occurs at the same time each day, often awakening patients from sleep. Attacks usually last 15-180 minutes and occur in clusters lasting weeks to months, followed by pain-free periods.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cluster headaches are characterised by unilateral autonomic symptoms including lacrimation, nasal congestion, and ptosis.","Cluster headaches typically occur in clusters lasting weeks to months, with pain-free periods in between.","Cluster headaches are more common in men and are often described as the most severe pain humans can experience."],"references":["Wei DY, Yuan Ong JJ, Goadsby PJ. Cluster Headache: Epidemiology, Pathophysiology, Clinical Features, and Diagnosis. Ann Indian Acad Neurol. 2018 Apr;21(Suppl 1):S3-S8. doi: 10.4103/aian.AIAN_349_17. PMID: 29720812; PMCID: PMC5909131.","Malu OO, Bailey J, Hawks MK. Cluster Headache: Rapid Evidence Review. Am Fam Physician. 2022 Jan 1;105(1):24-32. PMID: 35029932.","Kandel SA, Mandiga P. Cluster Headache. [Updated 2023 Jul 4]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK544241/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61379"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17179"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61379","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61379"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T05:21:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T05:21:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9869"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75866"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagG